ofessor [[Samuel Armistead]] and his colleagues, maintained by Professor Bruce Rosenstock.\n* [http://www.pizmonim.com/ Sephardic Pizmonim Project]- Music of the Middle Eastern Sephardic Community.\n* [http://www.danielhalfon.com/ Daniel Halfon] website of a British-born cantor and leading exponent of the liturgical tradition of Spanish and Portuguese Jews\n* [http://www.archivio-torah.it/audio/tefillot/canti%20scoletta/ Liturgy of the Spanish Synagogue in Rome] performed by Rev. Alberto Funaro\n* [http://www.isaacazose.com/ Isaac Azose] website of a cantor from Seattle, WA, USA, instrumental in preservation of the Sephardic liturgical tradition of Rhodes\n* [http://www.downhomeradioshow.com/2006/11/songs-of-the-sephardic-jewish-women-of-morocco/ Songs of the Sephardic Jewish Women of Morocco] Internet Radio Show featuring field recordings of Sephardic Jewish Women in Tangier & Tetuan, 1954 w/ song texts translated into English.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110908140444/http://www.vagabond.bg/jewishbulgaria/ A Guide to Jewish Bulgaria, published by Vagabond Media, Sofia, 2011]\n* [http://www.classicalacarte.net/Fiches/9809.htm Diaspora Sefardi - Jordi Savall, Hesp\u00e8rion XXI - Alia Vox AV9809]\n\n{{Ethnic groups in Israel}}\n{{Sephardi Jews topics}}\n{{Jews and Judaism}}\n{{Spanish diaspora}}\n\n[[Category:Sephardi Jews| ]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Canada]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in France]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Greece]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Israel]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Italy]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Morocco]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Spain]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Romania]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Tunisia]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in the United States]]\n[[Category:Jewish ethnic groups]]\n[[Category:Jews and Judaism in Europe]]\n[[Category:Sephardi Jews topics| ]]\n", "name_user": "Mozad655", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eJews in Muslim Iberia:More correct term inserted.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sephardi_Jews"}
{"title_page": "Osteoblast", "text_new": "{{Infobox cell\n| Name        = Osteoblast\n| Latin       = \n| Greek       = osteoblast\n| Image       = Bone hypercalcemia - cropped - very high mag.jpg\n| Caption     = <div style=\"text-align: left;\">'''Osteoblasts''' (purple) rimming a bony spicule (pink - on diagonal of image). In this routinely fixed and decalcified (bone mineral removed) tissue, the osteoblasts have retracted and are separated from each other and from their underlying matrix. In living bone, the cells are linked by [[tight junctions]] and [[gap junctions]], and integrated with underlying osteocytes and matrix [[H&E stain]].</div>\n| Width       = 200px\n| Image2      = Bone forming cells - Osteoblasts 3 -- Smart-Servier.png\n| Caption2    = Illustration showing a single osteoblast\n| Precursor   = \n| System      = \n| Function = Formation of [[bone tissue]]\n| Location = [[Bone]]\n}}\n'''Osteoblasts''' (from the [[Greek language|Greek]] combining forms for \"[[bone]]\", \u1f40\u03c3\u03c4\u03ad\u03bf-, ''osteo-'' and \u03b2\u03bb\u03b1\u03c3\u03c4\u03ac\u03bd\u03c9, ''blastan\u014d'' \"germinate\") are [[cell (biology)|cell]]s with a single [[Cell nucleus|nucleus]] that synthesize [[bone]]. However, in the process of [[bone formation]], osteoblasts function in groups of connected cells. Individual cells cannot make bone. A group of organized osteoblasts together with the bone made by a unit of cells is usually called the [[osteon]].\n\nOsteoblasts are specialized, terminally differentiated products of [[mesenchymal stem cell]]s.<ref name=\"pmid10102814\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Pittenger MF, Mackay AM, Beck SC, Jaiswal RK, Douglas R, Mosca JD, Moorman MA, Simonetti DW, Craig S, Marshak DR | title = Multilineage potential of adult human mesenchymal stem cells | journal = Science | volume = 284 | issue = 5411 | pages = 143\u20137 | date = April 1999 | pmid = 10102814 | doi = 10.1126/science.284.5411.143| bibcode = 1999Sci...284..143P }}</ref> They synthesize dense, crosslinked [[collagen]] and specialized proteins in much smaller quantities, including [[osteocalcin]] and [[osteopontin]], which compose the organic matrix of bone.\n\nIn organized groups of connected cells, osteoblasts produce [[hydroxylapatite]] - the [[bone mineral]], that is deposited in a highly regulated manner, into the organic matrix forming a strong and dense [[mineralized tissues|mineralized tissue]] - the mineralized matrix. The mineralized [[skeleton]] is the main support for the bodies of air breathing [[vertebrates]]. It is an important store of minerals for physiological [[homeostasis]] including both [[acid\u2013base homeostasis|acid-base balance]] and [[calcium]] or [[phosphate]] maintenance.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Arnett T | year = 2003 | title = Regulation of bone cell function by acid-base balance | url = | journal = Proc Nutr Soc. | volume = 62 | issue = | pages = 511\u201320 | pmid = 14506899 }}</ref><ref name=\"pmid18710437\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Blair HC, Zaidi M, Huang CL, Sun L | title = The developmental basis of skeletal cell differentiation and the molecular basis of major skeletal defects | journal = Biol Rev Camb Philos Soc | volume = 83 | issue = 4 | pages = 401\u201315 | date = November 2008 | pmid = 18710437 | doi = 10.1111/j.1469-185X.2008.00048.x }}</ref>\n\n== Bone structure ==\nThe [[skeleton]] is a large organ that is [[bone remodeling|formed and degraded]] throughout life in the air-breathing vertebrates. The skeleton, often referred to as the skeletal system, is important both as a supporting structure and for maintenance of calcium, phosphate, and [[acid\u2013base homeostasis|acid-base status]] in the whole organism.<ref name=\"pmid17646258\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Blair HC, Sun L, Kohanski RA | title = Balanced regulation of proliferation, growth, differentiation, and degradation in skeletal cells | journal = Ann. N. Y. Acad. Sci. | volume = 1116 | issue = 1| pages = 165\u201373 | date = November 2007 | pmid = 17646258 | doi = 10.1196/annals.1402.029 | bibcode = 2007NYASA1116..165B }}</ref> The functional part of bone, the ''bone matrix'', is entirely extracellular. The bone matrix consists of [[protein]] and [[mineral]]. The protein forms the ''organic matrix.'' It is synthesized and then the mineral is added. The vast majority of the organic matrix is [[collagen]], which provides [[tensile strength]]. The matrix is mineralized by deposition of hydroxyapatite (alternative name, hydroxylapatite). This mineral is hard, and provides [[compressive strength]]. Thus, the collagen and mineral together are a [[composite material]] with excellent tensile and compressive strength, which can bend under a strain and recover its shape without damage. This is called [[elastic deformation]]. Forces that exceed the capacity of bone to behave elastically may cause failure, typically [[bone fracture]]s.\n\n==Bone remodeling==\nBone is a dynamic tissue that is constantly being [[bone remodeling|reshaped by osteoblasts]], which produce and secrete matrix proteins and transport mineral into the matrix, and [[osteoclasts]], which break down the tissues.\n\n=== Osteoblasts ===\nOsteoblasts are the major cellular component of bone. Osteoblasts arise from [[mesenchymal stem cell]]s (MSC). MSC give rise to osteoblasts, [[adipocyte]]s, and [[myocyte]]s among other cell types. Osteoblast quantity is understood to be inversely proportional to that of marrow adipocytes which comprise [[Marrow Adipose Tissue|marrow adipose tissue (MAT)]]. Osteoblasts are found in large numbers in the [[periosteum]], the thin connective tissue layer on the outside surface of bones, and in the [[endosteum]].\n\nNormally, almost all of the bone matrix, in the air breathing [[vertebrate]]s, is mineralized by the osteoblasts. Before the organic matrix is mineralized, it is called the [[osteoid]]. Osteoblasts buried in the matrix are called [[osteocytes]]. During bone formation, the surface layer of osteoblasts consists of cuboidal cells, called ''active osteoblasts'''''.''' When the bone-forming unit is not actively synthesizing bone, the surface osteoblasts are flattened and are called ''inactive osteoblasts''. Osteocytes remain alive and are connected by cell processes to a surface layer of osteoblasts. Osteocytes have important functions in skeletal maintenance.\n\n=== Osteoclasts ===\nOsteoclasts are multinucleated cells that derive from hematopoietic progenitors in the bone marrow which also give rise to monocytes in peripheral blood.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Loutit |first1=J.F. |last2=Nisbet |first2=N.W. |title=The Origin of Osteoclasts |journal=Immunobiology |date=January 1982 |volume=161 |issue=3\u20134 |pages=193\u2013203 |doi=10.1016/S0171-2985(82)80074-0 |pmid=7047369 }}</ref> Osteoclasts break down bone tissue, and along with osteoblasts and osteocytes form the structural components of bone. In the hollow within bones are many other cell types of the [[bone marrow]]. Components that are essential for osteoblast bone formation include mesenchymal stem cells (osteoblast precursor) and [[blood vessels]] that supply oxygen and nutrients for bone formation. Bone is a highly vascular tissue, and active formation of blood vessel cells, also from mesenchymal stem cells, is essential to support the metabolic activity of bone. The balance of bone formation and [[bone resorption]] tends to be negative with age, particularly in post-menopausal women,<ref name=\"pmid20425612\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Nicks KM, Fowler TW, Gaddy D | title = Reproductive hormones and bone | journal = Curr Osteoporos Rep | volume = 8 | issue = 2 | pages = 60\u20137 | date = June 2010 | pmid = 20425612 | doi = 10.1007/s11914-010-0014-3 }}</ref> often leading to a loss of bone serious enough to cause fractures, which is called [[osteoporosis]].\n\n==Osteogenesis==\nBone is formed by one of two processes: [[endochondral ossification]] or [[intramembranous ossification]]. Endochondral ossification is the process of forming bone from cartilage and this is the usual method. This form of [[Bone#Development|bone development]] is the more complex form: it follows the formation of a first skeleton of [[cartilage]] made by [[chondrocyte]]s, which is then removed and replaced by bone, made by osteoblasts. Intramembranous ossification is the direct ossification of [[mesenchyme]] as happens during the formation of the [[membrane bone]]s of the skull and others.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Larsen|first1=William J.|title=Human embryology|date=2001|publisher=Churchill Livingstone|location=Philadelphia, Pa.|isbn=0-443-06583-7|pages=355\u2013357|edition=3.}}</ref>\n\nDuring osteoblast [[cellular differentiation|differentiation]], [[Osteochondroprogenitor cell|the developing progenitor cell]]s express the regulatory [[transcription factor]] [[Cbfa1|Cbfa1/Runx2]]. A second required transcription factor is [[Sp7 transcription factor]].<ref name=\"pmid18767962\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Karsenty G | title = Transcriptional control of skeletogenesis | journal = Annu Rev Genom Hum Genet | volume = 9 | issue = | pages = 183\u201396 | date = 2008 | pmid = 18767962 | doi = 10.1146/annurev.genom.9.081307.164437 }}</ref> [[Osteochondroprogenitor cell]]s differentiate under the influence of [[growth factor]]s, although isolated mesenchymal stem cells in tissue culture, form osteoblasts under permissive conditions that include [[vitamin C]] and substrates for [[alkaline phosphatase]], a key [[enzyme]] that provides high concentrations of phosphate at the mineral deposition site.<ref name=\"pmid10102814\"/>\n\n=== Bone morphogenetic proteins ===\nKey growth factors in endochondral skeletal differentiation include [[bone morphogenetic protein]]s (BMPs) that determine to a major extent where chondrocyte differentiation occurs and where spaces are left between bones. The system of cartilage replacement by bone has a complex regulatory system. [[Bone morphogenetic protein 2|BMP2]] also regulates early skeletal patterning. [[transforming growth factor beta]] (TGF-\u03b2), is part of a superfamily of proteins that include BMPs, which possess common signaling elements in the [[TGF beta signaling pathway]]. TGF-\u03b2 is particularly important in [[cartilage]] differentiation, which generally precedes bone formation for endochondral ossification. An additional family of essential regulatory factors is the [[fibroblast growth factor]]s (FGFs) that determine where skeletal elements occur in relation to the skin\n\n===Steroid and protein hormones===\nMany other regulatory systems are involved in the transition of cartilage to bone and in bone maintenance. A particularly important bone-targeted hormonal regulator is [[parathyroid hormone]] (PTH). Parathyroid hormone is a protein made by the [[parathyroid]] gland under the control of serum calcium activity.<ref name=\"pmid18710437\"/> PTH also has important systemic functions, including to keep serum calcium concentrations nearly constant regardless of calcium intake. Increasing dietary calcium results in minor increases in blood calcium. However, this is not a significant mechanism supporting osteoblast bone formation, except in the condition of low dietary calcium; further, abnormally high dietary calcium raises the risk of serious health consequences not directly related to bone mass including [[Myocardial infarction|heart attack]] and [[stroke]].<ref name=\"pmid25491763\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Reid IR, Bristow SM, Bolland MJ | title = Cardiovascular complications of calcium supplements | journal = J. Cell. Biochem. | volume = 116 | issue = 4 | pages = 494\u2013501 | date = April 2015 | pmid = 25491763 | doi = 10.1002/jcb.25028 }}</ref> Intermittent PTH stimulation increases osteoblast activity, although PTH is bifunctional and mediates bone matrix degradation at higher concentrations.\n\nThe skeleton is also modified for reproduction and in response to nutritional and other [[hormone]] stresses; it responds to [[steroid]]s, including [[estrogen]] and [[glucocorticoid]]s, which are important in reproduction and energy metabolism regulation. Bone turnover involves major expenditures of energy for synthesis and degradation, involving many additional signals including [[pituitary]] hormones. Two of these are [[adrenocorticotropic hormone]] (ACTH)<ref name=\"pmid20421485\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Zaidi M, Sun L, Robinson LJ, Tourkova IL, Liu L, Wang Y, Zhu LL, Liu X, Li J, Peng Y, Yang G, Shi X, Levine A, Iqbal J, Yaroslavskiy BB, Isales C, Blair HC | title = ACTH protects against glucocorticoid-induced osteonecrosis of bone | journal = Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U.S.A. | volume = 107 | issue = 19 | pages = 8782\u20137 | date = May 2010 | pmid = 20421485 | pmc = 2889316 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.0912176107 | bibcode = 2010PNAS..107.8782Z }}</ref> and [[follicle stimulating hormone]].<ref name=\"pmid16630814\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Sun L, Peng Y, Sharrow AC, Iqbal J, Zhang Z, Papachristou DJ, Zaidi S, Zhu LL, Yaroslavskiy BB, Zhou H, Zallone A, Sairam MR, Kumar TR, Bo W, Braun J, Cardoso-Landa L, Schaffler MB, Moonga BS, Blair HC, Zaidi M | title = FSH directly regulates bone mass | journal = Cell | volume = 125 | issue = 2 | pages = 247\u201360 | date = April 2006 | pmid = 16630814 | doi = 10.1016/j.cell.2006.01.051 }}</ref> The physiological role for responses to these, and several other [[glycoprotein]] hormones, is not fully understood, although it is likely that ACTH is bifunctional, like PTH, supporting bone formation with periodic spikes of ACTH, but causing bone destruction in large concentrations. In mice, mutations that reduce the efficiency of ACTH-induced glucocorticoid production in the adrenals cause the skeleton to become dense ([[Osteosclerosis|osteosclerotic]] bone).<ref name=\"pmid18204096\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Hoekstra M, Meurs I, Koenders M, Out R, Hildebrand RB, Kruijt JK, Van Eck M, Van Berkel TJ | title = Absence of HDL cholesteryl ester uptake in mice via SR-BI impairs an adequate adrenal glucocorticoid-mediated stress response to fasting | journal = J. Lipid Res. | volume = 49 | issue = 4 | pages = 738\u201345 | date = April 2008 | pmid = 18204096 | doi = 10.1194/jlr.M700475-JLR200 }}</ref><ref name=\"pmid24253048\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Martineau C, Martin-Falstrault L, Brissette L, Moreau R | title = The atherogenic Scarb1 null mouse model shows a high bone mass phenotype | journal = Am. J. Physiol. Endocrinol. Metab. | volume = 306 | issue = 1 | pages = E48\u201357 | date = January 2014 | pmid = 24253048 | pmc = 3920004 | doi = 10.1152/ajpendo.00421.2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Organization and ultrastructure==\nIn well-preserved bone studied at high magnification via [[electron microscope|electron microscopy]], individual osteoblasts are shown to be connected by [[tight junctions]], which prevent [[extracellular fluid]] passage and thus create a bone compartment separate from the general extracellular fluid.<ref name=\"pmid8527235\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Arana-Chavez VE, Soares AM, Katchburian E | title = Junctions between early developing osteoblasts of rat calvaria as revealed by freeze-fracture and ultrathin section electron microscopy | journal = Arch. Histol. Cytol. | volume = 58 | issue = 3 | pages = 285\u201392 | date = August 1995 | pmid = 8527235 | doi=10.1679/aohc.58.285}}</ref> The osteoblasts are also connected by [[gap junction]]s, small pores that connect osteoblasts, allowing the cells in one cohort to function as a unit.<ref name=\"pmid6797704\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Doty SB | title = Morphological evidence of gap junctions between bone cells | journal = Calcif. Tissue Int. | volume = 33 | issue = 5 | pages = 509\u201312 | date = 1981 | pmid = 6797704 | doi = 10.1007/BF02409482 }}</ref> The gap junctions also connect deeper layers of cells to the surface layer (''osteocytes'' when surrounded by bone). This was demonstrated directly by injecting low [[molecular weight]] [[Fluorophore|fluorescent dyes]] into osteoblasts and showing that the dye diffused to surrounding and deeper cells in the bone-forming unit.<ref name=\"pmid10703922\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Yellowley CE, Li Z, Zhou Z, Jacobs CR, Donahue HJ | title = Functional gap junctions between osteocytic and osteoblastic cells | journal = J. Bone Miner. Res. | volume = 15 | issue = 2 | pages = 209\u201317 | date = February 2000 | pmid = 10703922 | doi = 10.1359/jbmr.2000.15.2.209 }}</ref> Bone is composed of many of these units, which are separated by impermeable zones with no cellular connections, called cement lines.\n\n==Collagen and accessory proteins==\nAlmost all of the organic (non-mineral) component of bone is dense [[collagen]] type I,<ref name=\"pmid271986\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Reddi AH, Gay R, Gay S, Miller EJ | title = Transitions in collagen types during matrix-induced cartilage, bone, and bone marrow formation | journal = Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U.S.A. | volume = 74 | issue = 12 | pages = 5589\u201392 | date = December 1977 | pmid = 271986 | pmc = 431820 | doi=10.1073/pnas.74.12.5589| bibcode = 1977PNAS...74.5589R }}</ref> which forms dense crosslinked ropes that give bone its tensile strength. By mechanisms still unclear, osteoblasts secrete layers of oriented collagen, with the layers parallel to the long axis of the bone alternating with layers at right angles to the long axis of the bone every few [[micrometers]]. Defects in collagen type I cause the commonest inherited disorder of bone, called [[osteogenesis imperfecta]].<ref name=\"pmid2010058\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Kuivaniemi H, Tromp G, Prockop DJ | title = Mutations in collagen genes: causes of rare and some common diseases in humans | journal = FASEB J. | volume = 5 | issue = 7 | pages = 2052\u201360 | date = April 1991 | pmid = 2010058 | doi = 10.1096/fasebj.5.7.2010058 }}</ref>\n\nMinor, but important, amounts of small proteins, including [[osteocalcin]] and [[osteopontin]], are secreted in bone's organic matrix.<ref name=\"pmid8579903\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Aubin JE, Liu F, Malaval L, Gupta AK | title = Osteoblast and chondroblast differentiation | journal = Bone | volume = 17 | issue = 2 Suppl | pages = 77S\u201383S | date = August 1995 | pmid = 8579903 | doi = 10.1016/8756-3282(95)00183-E }}</ref> Osteocalcin is not expressed at significant concentrations except in bone, and thus osteocalcin is a specific marker for bone matrix synthesis.<ref name=\"pmid2939433\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Delmas PD, Demiaux B, Malaval L, Chapuy MC, Meunier PJ | title = [Osteocalcin (or bone gla-protein), a new biological marker for studying bone pathology] | language = French | journal = Presse Med | volume = 15 | issue = 14 | pages = 643\u20136 | date = April 1986 | pmid = 2939433 }}</ref> These proteins link organic and mineral component of bone matrix.<ref name=\"pmid8075622\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Roach HI | title = Why does bone matrix contain non-collagenous proteins? The possible roles of osteocalcin, osteonectin, osteopontin and bone sialoprotein in bone mineralisation and resorption | journal = Cell Biol. Int. | volume = 18 | issue = 6 | pages = 617\u201328 | date = June 1994 | pmid = 8075622 | doi = 10.1006/cbir.1994.1088 }}</ref> The proteins are necessary for maximal matrix strength due to their intermediate localization between mineral and collagen.\n\nHowever, in mice where expression of osteocalcin or osteopontin was eliminated by targeted disruption of the respective genes ([[knockout mice]]), accumulation of mineral was not notably affected, indicating that organization of matrix is not significantly related to mineral transport.<ref name=\"pmid9737340\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Boskey AL, Gadaleta S, Gundberg C, Doty SB, Ducy P, Karsenty G | title = Fourier transform infrared microspectroscopic analysis of bones of osteocalcin-deficient mice provides insight into the function of osteocalcin | journal = Bone | volume = 23 | issue = 3 | pages = 187\u201396 | date = September 1998 | pmid = 9737340 | doi=10.1016/s8756-3282(98)00092-1}}</ref><ref name=\"pmid20171304\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Thurner PJ, Chen CG, Ionova-Martin S, Sun L, Harman A, Porter A, Ager JW, Ritchie RO, Alliston T | title = Osteopontin deficiency increases bone fragility but preserves bone mass | journal = Bone | volume = 46 | issue = 6 | pages = 1564\u201373 | date = June 2010 | pmid = 20171304 | pmc = 2875278 | doi = 10.1016/j.bone.2010.02.014 }}</ref>\n\n==Bone versus cartilage==\nThe primitive skeleton is [[cartilage]], a solid avascular (without blood vessels) tissue in which individual cartilage-matrix secreting cells, or [[chondrocyte]]s, occur. Chondrocytes do not have intercellular connections and are not coordinated in units. Cartilage is composed of a network of [[collagen]] type II held in tension by water-absorbing proteins, hydrophilic [[proteoglycan]]s.<ref name=\"pmid12023876\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Blair HC, Zaidi M, Schlesinger PH | title = Mechanisms balancing skeletal matrix synthesis and degradation | journal = Biochem. J. | volume = 364 | issue = Pt 2 | pages = 329\u201341 | date = June 2002 | pmid = 12023876 | doi = 10.1042/BJ20020165 | pmc = 1222578 }}</ref> This is the adult skeleton in [[Chondrichthyes|cartilaginous fishes]] such as [[shark]]s. It develops as the initial skeleton in more advanced [[Class (biology)|classes]] of animals.\n\nIn air-breathing vertebrates, cartilage is replaced by cellular bone. A transitional tissue is mineralized [[cartilage]]. Cartilage mineralizes by massive expression of phosphate-producing enzymes, which cause high local concentrations of calcium and phosphate that precipitate.<ref name=\"pmid12023876\"/> This mineralized cartilage is not dense or strong. In the air breathing vertebrates it is used as a scaffold for formation of cellular bone made by osteoblasts, and then it is removed by [[osteoclasts]], which specialize in degrading mineralized tissue.\n\nOsteoblasts produce an advanced type of bone matrix consisting of dense, irregular crystals of [[hydroxyapatite]], packed around the collagen ropes.<ref name=\"pmid21674636\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Blair HC, Robinson LJ, Huang CL, Sun L, Friedman PA, Schlesinger PH, Zaidi M | title = Calcium and bone disease | journal = BioFactors | volume = 37 | issue = 3 | pages = 159\u201367 | date = 2011 | pmid = 21674636 | pmc = 3608212 | doi = 10.1002/biof.143 }}</ref> This is a strong composite material that allows the skeleton to be shaped mainly as hollow tubes. Reducing the long bones to tubes reduces weight while maintaining strength.\n\n==Mineralization of bone==\nThe mechanisms of mineralization are not fully understood. Fluorescent, low-molecular weight compounds such as [[tetracycline]] or [[calcein]] bind strongly to bone mineral, when administered for short periods. They then accumulate in narrow bands in the new bone.<ref name=\"pmid4894738\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Frost HM | title = Tetracycline-based histological analysis of bone remodeling | journal = Calcif Tissue Res | volume = 3 | issue = 1 | pages = 211\u201337 | date = 1969 | pmid = 4894738 | doi = 10.1007/BF02058664 }}</ref> These bands run across the contiguous group of bone-forming osteoblasts. They occur at a narrow (sub-[[micrometer]]) mineralization front. Most bone surfaces express no new bone formation, no tetracycline uptake and no mineral formation. This strongly suggests that facilitated or [[active transport]], coordinated across the bone-forming group, is involved in bone formation, and that only cell-mediated mineral formation occurs. That is, dietary calcium does not create mineral by mass action.\n\nThe mechanism of mineral formation in bone is clearly distinct from the [[phylogenetic]]ally older process by which cartilage is mineralized: tetracycline does not label mineralized cartilage at narrow bands or in specific sites, but diffusely, in keeping with a passive mineralization mechanism.<ref name=\"pmid21674636\"/>\n\nOsteoblasts separate bone from the extracellular fluid by tight junctions <ref name=\"pmid8527235\"/> by regulated transport. Unlike in cartilage, [[phosphate]] and [[calcium]] cannot move in or out by passive diffusion, because the [[tight junction|tight osteoblast junction]]s isolate the bone formation space. Calcium is transported across osteoblasts by [[facilitated transport]] (that is, by passive transporters, which do not pump calcium against a gradient).<ref name=\"pmid21674636\"/> In contrast, phosphate is actively produced by a combination of secretion of phosphate-containing compounds, including [[Adenosine triphosphate|ATP]], and by [[phosphatase]]s that cleave phosphate to create a high phosphate concentration at the mineralization front. [[Alkaline phosphatase]] is a membrane-anchored protein that is a characteristic marker expressed in large amounts at the apical (secretory) face of active osteoblasts.\n\n[[File:Osteoblast Organization.jpg|thumb|'''Major features of the bone-forming complex''', the osteon, composed of osteoblasts and osteocytes.]]\n\nAt least one more regulated transport process is involved. The [[stoichiometry]] of bone mineral basically is that of [[Hydroxylapatite|hydroxyapatite]] precipitating from phosphate, calcium, and water at a slightly alkaline [[pH]]:<ref name=\"Neuman1958\">{{cite book|vauthors = Neuman WF, Neuman MW|title=The Chemical Dynamics of Bone Mineral|url = https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.550358|date=1958-01-01|publisher = University of Chicago Press|isbn = 0-226-57512-8}}{{page needed|date=October 2019}}</ref>\n\n               '''6 HPO<sub>4</sub><sup>2\u2212</sup> + 2 H<sub>2</sub>O + 10 Ca<sup>2+</sup> \u21cc Ca<sub>10</sub>(PO<sub>4</sub>)<sub>6</sub>(OH)<sub>2</sub> + {{color|red|8 H<sup>+</sup>}}'''\n\nIn a closed system as mineral precipitates, acid accumulates, rapidly lowering the [[pH]] and stopping further precipitation. Cartilage presents no barrier to diffusion and acid therefore diffuses away, allowing precipitation to continue. In the osteon, where matrix is separated from extracellular fluid by tight junctions, this cannot occur. In the controlled, sealed compartment, removing H<sup>+</sup> drives precipitation under a wide variety of extracellular conditions, as long as calcium and phosphate are available in the matrix compartment.<ref name=\"pmid14498063\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Schartum S, Nichols G | title = Concerning pH gradients between the extracellular compartment and fluids bathing the bone mineral surface and their relation to calcium ion distribution | journal = J. Clin. Invest. | volume = 41 | issue = 5| pages = 1163\u20138 | date = May 1962 | pmid = 14498063 | pmc = 291024 | doi = 10.1172/JCI104569 }}</ref> The mechanism by which acid transits the barrier layer remains uncertain. Osteoblasts have capacity for Na<sup>+</sup>/H<sup>+</sup> exchange via the redundant Na/H exchangers, NHE1 and NHE6.<ref name=\"pmid21413028\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Liu L, Schlesinger PH, Slack NM, Friedman PA, Blair HC | title = High capacity Na+/H+ exchange activity in mineralizing osteoblasts | journal = J. Cell. Physiol. | volume = 226 | issue = 6 | pages = 1702\u201312 | date = June 2011 | pmid = 21413028 | pmc = 4458346 | doi = 10.1002/jcp.22501 }}</ref> This H<sup>+</sup> exchange is a major element in acid removal, although the mechanism by which H<sup>+</sup> is transported from the matrix space into the barrier osteoblast is not known.\n\nIn bone removal, a reverse transport mechanism uses acid delivered to the mineralized matrix to drive hydroxyapatite into solution.<ref name=\"pmid2528207\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Blair HC, Teitelbaum SL, Ghiselli R, Gluck S | title = Osteoclastic bone resorption by a polarized vacuolar proton pump | journal = Science | volume = 245 | issue = 4920 | pages = 855\u20137 | date = August 1989 | pmid = 2528207 | doi=10.1126/science.2528207| bibcode = 1989Sci...245..855B }}</ref>\n\n== Osteocyte feedback ==\nFeedback from physical activity maintains bone mass, while feedback from osteocytes limits the size of the bone-forming unit.<ref name=\"pmid16036059\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Klein-Nulend J, Nijweide PJ, Burger EH | title = Osteocyte and bone structure | journal = Curr Osteoporos Rep | volume = 1 | issue = 1 | pages = 5\u201310 | date = June 2003 | pmid = 16036059 | doi=10.1007/s11914-003-0002-y}}</ref> An important additional mechanism is secretion by osteocytes, buried in the matrix, of [[sclerostin]], a protein that inhibits a pathway that maintains osteoblast activity. Thus, when the osteon reaches a limiting size, it deactivates bone synthesis.<ref name=\"pmid17118265\">{{cite book |doi=10.1016/S0070-2153(06)76004-5 |pmid=17118265 |chapter=WNT Signaling: A Key Regulator of Bone Mass |volume=76 |pages=103\u2013127 |title=Current Topics in Developmental Biology |year=2006 |last1=Baron |first1=Roland |last2=Rawadi |first2=Georges |last3=Roman\u2010Roman |first3=Sergio |isbn=978-0-12-153176-8 }}</ref>\n\n==Morphology and histological staining==\n\n[[H&E stain|Hematoxylin and eosin]] staining (H&E) shows that the cytoplasm of active osteoblasts is slightly [[basophilic]] due to the substantial presence of [[Endoplasmic reticulum#Rough endoplasmic reticulum|rough endoplasmic reticulum]]. The active osteoblast produces substantial collagen type I. About 10% of the bone matrix is collagen with the balance mineral.<ref name=\"Neuman1958\"/> The osteoblast's nucleus is spherical and large. An active osteoblast is characterized morphologically by a prominent [[Golgi apparatus]] that appears histologically as a clear zone adjacent to the nucleus. The products of the cell are mostly for transport into the osteoid, the non-mineralized matrix. Active osteoblasts can be labeled by antibodies to [[Type-I collagen]], or using naphthol phosphate and the [[Diazonium compound|diazonium]] dye fast blue to demonstrate alkaline phosphatase [[enzyme]] activity directly.\n\n<gallery>\nImage:Osteoblast.jpg | Osteoblast (Wright Giemsa stain, 100x) \nImage:Active osteoblasts.jpg |[[Micrograph|Light micrograph]] of [[Bone decalcification|decalcified]]  cancellous bone displaying osteoblasts actively synthesizing osteoid, containing two osteocytes.\nImage:Bony_nidus_2.jpg|[[Micrograph|Light micrograph]] of undecalcified tissue displaying osteoblasts actively synthesizing osteoid (center).\nImage:Bony_nidus_3.jpg|[[Micrograph|Light micrograph]] of undecalcified tissue displaying osteoblasts actively synthesizing rudimentary bone tissue (center).\nImage:Bone_hypercalcemia_-_2_-_very_high_mag.jpg|Osteoblasts lining bone (H&E stain).\n</gallery>\n\n==Isolation of Osteoblasts==\n#The first isolation technique by microdissection method was originally described by Fell et al.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Fell |first1=HB |title=The Osteogenic Capacity in vitro of Periosteum and Endosteum Isolated from the Limb Skeleton of Fowl Embryos and Young Chicks. |journal=Journal of Anatomy |date=January 1932 |volume=66 |issue=Pt 2 |pages=157\u2013180.11 |pmid=17104365 |pmc=1248877 }}</ref> using chick limb bones which were separated into periosteum and remaining parts. She obtained cells which possessed osteogenic characteristics from cultured tissue using chick limb bones which were separated into periosteum and remaining parts. She obtained cells which possessed osteogenic characteristics from cultured tissue. \n#Enzymatic digestion is one of the most advanced techniques for isolating bone cell populations and obtaining osteoblasts. Peck et al. (1964)<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Peck |first1=W. A. |last2=Birge |first2=S. J. |last3=Fedak |first3=S. A. |title=Bone Cells: Biochemical and Biological Studies after Enzymatic Isolation |journal=Science |date=11 December 1964 |volume=146 |issue=3650 |pages=1476\u20131477 |doi=10.1126/science.146.3650.1476 |pmid=14208576 |bibcode=1964Sci...146.1476P }}</ref> described the original method that is now often used by many researchers.\n#In 1974 Jones et al.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Jones |first1=S.J. |last2=Boyde |first2=A. |title=Some morphological observations on osteoclasts |journal=Cell and Tissue Research |date=December 1977 |volume=185 |issue=3 |pages=387\u201397 |doi=10.1007/bf00220298 |pmid=597853 }}</ref> found that osteoblasts moved laterally in vivo and in vitro under different experimental conditions and escribed the migration method in detail. The osteoblasts were, however, contaminated by cells migrating from the vascular openings, which might include endothelial cells and fibroblasts.\n\n== See also ==\n*[[List of human cell types derived from the germ layers]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*[[William F. Neuman]] and Margaret W. Neuman. (1958). The Chemical Dynamics of Bone Mineral. Chicago: The University of Chicago Press. {{ISBN|0-226-57512-8}}.\n*[[Frank H. Netter|Netter, Frank H.]] (1987). ''Musculoskeletal system: anatomy, physiology, and metabolic disorders''. Summit, New Jersey: Ciba-Geigy Corporation {{ISBN|0-914168-88-6}}.\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Bone and cartilage}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Skeletal system]]\n[[Category:Connective tissue cells]]\n[[Category:Human cells]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox cell\n| Name        = Osteoblast\n| Latin       = \n| Greek       = osteoblast\n| Image       = Bone hypercalcemia - cropped - very high mag.jpg\n| Caption     = <div style=\"text-align: left;\">'''Osteoblasts''' (purple) rimming a bony spicule (pink - on diagonal of image). In this routinely fixed and decalcified (bone mineral removed) tissue, the osteoblasts have retracted and are separated from each other and from their underlying matrix. In living bone, the cells are linked by [[tight junctions]] and [[gap junctions]], and integrated with underlying osteocytes and matrix [[H&E stain]].</div>\n| Width       = 200px\n| Image2      = Bone forming cells - Osteoblasts 3 -- Smart-Servier.png\n| Caption2    = Illustration showing a single osteoblast\n| Precursor   = \n| System      = \n| Function = Formation of [[bone tissue]]\n| Location = [[Bone]]\n}}\n'''Osteoblasts''' (from the [[Greek language|Greek]] combining forms for \"[[bone]]\", \u1f40\u03c3\u03c4\u03ad\u03bf-, ''osteo-'' and \u03b2\u03bb\u03b1\u03c3\u03c4\u03ac\u03bd\u03c9, ''blastan\u014d'' \"germinate\") are [[cell (biology)|cell]]s with a single [[Cell nucleus|nucleus]] that synthesize [[bone]]. However, in the process of [[bone formation]], osteoblasts function in groups of connected cells. Individual cells cannot make bone. A group of organized osteoblasts together with the bone made by a unit of cells is usually called the [[osteon]].\n\nOsteoblasts are specialized, terminally differentiated products of [[mesenchymal stem cell]]s.<ref name=\"pmid10102814\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Pittenger MF, Mackay AM, Beck SC, Jaiswal RK, Douglas R, Mosca JD, Moorman MA, Simonetti DW, Craig S, Marshak DR | title = Multilineage potential of adult human mesenchymal stem cells | journal = Science | volume = 284 | issue = 5411 | pages = 143\u20137 | date = April 1999 | pmid = 10102814 | doi = 10.1126/science.284.5411.143| bibcode = 1999Sci...284..143P }}</ref> They synthesize dense, crosslinked [[collagen]] and specialized proteins in much smaller quantities, including [[osteocalcin]] and [[osteopontin]], which compose the organic matrix of bone.\n\nIn organized groups of connected cells, osteoblasts produce [[hydroxylapatite]] - the [[bone mineral]], that is deposited in a highly regulated manner, into the organic matrix forming a strong and dense [[mineralized tissues|mineralized tissue]] - the mineralized matrix. The mineralized [[skeleton]] is the main support for the bodies of air breathing [[vertebrates]]. It is an important store of minerals for physiological [[homeostasis]] including both [[acid\u2013base homeostasis|acid-base balance]] and [[calcium]] or [[phosphate]] maintenance.<ref>Arnett T. (2003). Regulation of bone cell function by acid-base balance. Proc Nutr Soc. 62: 511-20. {{PMID|14506899}}.</ref><ref name=\"pmid18710437\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Blair HC, Zaidi M, Huang CL, Sun L | title = The developmental basis of skeletal cell differentiation and the molecular basis of major skeletal defects | journal = Biol Rev Camb Philos Soc | volume = 83 | issue = 4 | pages = 401\u201315 | date = November 2008 | pmid = 18710437 | doi = 10.1111/j.1469-185X.2008.00048.x }}</ref>\n\n== Bone structure ==\nThe [[skeleton]] is a large organ that is [[bone remodeling|formed and degraded]] throughout life in the air-breathing vertebrates. The skeleton, often referred to as the skeletal system, is important both as a supporting structure and for maintenance of calcium, phosphate, and [[acid\u2013base homeostasis|acid-base status]] in the whole organism.<ref name=\"pmid17646258\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Blair HC, Sun L, Kohanski RA | title = Balanced regulation of proliferation, growth, differentiation, and degradation in skeletal cells | journal = Ann. N. Y. Acad. Sci. | volume = 1116 | issue = 1| pages = 165\u201373 | date = November 2007 | pmid = 17646258 | doi = 10.1196/annals.1402.029 | bibcode = 2007NYASA1116..165B }}</ref> The functional part of bone, the ''bone matrix'', is entirely extracellular. The bone matrix consists of [[protein]] and [[mineral]]. The protein forms the ''organic matrix.'' It is synthesized and then the mineral is added. The vast majority of the organic matrix is [[collagen]], which provides [[tensile strength]]. The matrix is mineralized by deposition of hydroxyapatite (alternative name, hydroxylapatite). This mineral is hard, and provides [[compressive strength]]. Thus, the collagen and mineral together are a [[composite material]] with excellent tensile and compressive strength, which can bend under a strain and recover its shape without damage. This is called [[elastic deformation]]. Forces that exceed the capacity of bone to behave elastically may cause failure, typically [[bone fracture]]s.\n\n==Bone remodeling==\nBone is a dynamic tissue that is constantly being [[bone remodeling|reshaped by osteoblasts]], which produce and secrete matrix proteins and transport mineral into the matrix, and [[osteoclasts]], which break down the tissues.\n\n=== Osteoblasts ===\nOsteoblasts are the major cellular component of bone. Osteoblasts arise from [[mesenchymal stem cell]]s (MSC). MSC give rise to osteoblasts, [[adipocyte]]s, and [[myocyte]]s among other cell types. Osteoblast quantity is understood to be inversely proportional to that of marrow adipocytes which comprise [[Marrow Adipose Tissue|marrow adipose tissue (MAT)]]. Osteoblasts are found in large numbers in the [[periosteum]], the thin connective tissue layer on the outside surface of bones, and in the [[endosteum]].\n\nNormally, almost all of the bone matrix, in the air breathing [[vertebrate]]s, is mineralized by the osteoblasts. Before the organic matrix is mineralized, it is called the [[osteoid]]. Osteoblasts buried in the matrix are called [[osteocytes]]. During bone formation, the surface layer of osteoblasts consists of cuboidal cells, called ''active osteoblasts'''''.''' When the bone-forming unit is not actively synthesizing bone, the surface osteoblasts are flattened and are called ''inactive osteoblasts''. Osteocytes remain alive and are connected by cell processes to a surface layer of osteoblasts. Osteocytes have important functions in skeletal maintenance.\n\n=== Osteoclasts ===\nOsteoclasts are multinucleated cells that derive from hematopoietic progenitors in the bone marrow which also give rise to monocytes in peripheral blood.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Loutit |first1=J.F. |last2=Nisbet |first2=N.W. |title=The Origin of Osteoclasts |journal=Immunobiology |date=January 1982 |volume=161 |issue=3\u20134 |pages=193\u2013203 |doi=10.1016/S0171-2985(82)80074-0 |pmid=7047369 }}</ref> Osteoclasts break down bone tissue, and along with osteoblasts and osteocytes form the structural components of bone. In the hollow within bones are many other cell types of the [[bone marrow]]. Components that are essential for osteoblast bone formation include mesenchymal stem cells (osteoblast precursor) and [[blood vessels]] that supply oxygen and nutrients for bone formation. Bone is a highly vascular tissue, and active formation of blood vessel cells, also from mesenchymal stem cells, is essential to support the metabolic activity of bone. The balance of bone formation and [[bone resorption]] tends to be negative with age, particularly in post-menopausal women,<ref name=\"pmid20425612\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Nicks KM, Fowler TW, Gaddy D | title = Reproductive hormones and bone | journal = Curr Osteoporos Rep | volume = 8 | issue = 2 | pages = 60\u20137 | date = June 2010 | pmid = 20425612 | doi = 10.1007/s11914-010-0014-3 }}</ref> often leading to a loss of bone serious enough to cause fractures, which is called [[osteoporosis]].\n\n==Osteogenesis==\nBone is formed by one of two processes: [[endochondral ossification]] or [[intramembranous ossification]]. Endochondral ossification is the process of forming bone from cartilage and this is the usual method. This form of [[Bone#Development|bone development]] is the more complex form: it follows the formation of a first skeleton of [[cartilage]] made by [[chondrocyte]]s, which is then removed and replaced by bone, made by osteoblasts. Intramembranous ossification is the direct ossification of [[mesenchyme]] as happens during the formation of the [[membrane bone]]s of the skull and others.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Larsen|first1=William J.|title=Human embryology|date=2001|publisher=Churchill Livingstone|location=Philadelphia, Pa.|isbn=0-443-06583-7|pages=355\u2013357|edition=3.}}</ref>\n\nDuring osteoblast [[cellular differentiation|differentiation]], [[Osteochondroprogenitor cell|the developing progenitor cell]]s express the regulatory [[transcription factor]] [[Cbfa1|Cbfa1/Runx2]]. A second required transcription factor is [[Sp7 transcription factor]].<ref name=\"pmid18767962\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Karsenty G | title = Transcriptional control of skeletogenesis | journal = Annu Rev Genom Hum Genet | volume = 9 | issue = | pages = 183\u201396 | date = 2008 | pmid = 18767962 | doi = 10.1146/annurev.genom.9.081307.164437 }}</ref> [[Osteochondroprogenitor cell]]s differentiate under the influence of [[growth factor]]s, although isolated mesenchymal stem cells in tissue culture, form osteoblasts under permissive conditions that include [[vitamin C]] and substrates for [[alkaline phosphatase]], a key [[enzyme]] that provides high concentrations of phosphate at the mineral deposition site.<ref name=\"pmid10102814\"/>\n\n=== Bone morphogenetic proteins ===\nKey growth factors in endochondral skeletal differentiation include [[bone morphogenetic protein]]s (BMPs) that determine to a major extent where chondrocyte differentiation occurs and where spaces are left between bones. The system of cartilage replacement by bone has a complex regulatory system. [[Bone morphogenetic protein 2|BMP2]] also regulates early skeletal patterning. [[transforming growth factor beta]] (TGF-\u03b2), is part of a superfamily of proteins that include BMPs, which possess common signaling elements in the [[TGF beta signaling pathway]]. TGF-\u03b2 is particularly important in [[cartilage]] differentiation, which generally precedes bone formation for endochondral ossification. An additional family of essential regulatory factors is the [[fibroblast growth factor]]s (FGFs) that determine where skeletal elements occur in relation to the skin\n\n===Steroid and protein hormones===\nMany other regulatory systems are involved in the transition of cartilage to bone and in bone maintenance. A particularly important bone-targeted hormonal regulator is [[parathyroid hormone]] (PTH). Parathyroid hormone is a protein made by the [[parathyroid]] gland under the control of serum calcium activity.<ref name=\"pmid18710437\"/> PTH also has important systemic functions, including to keep serum calcium concentrations nearly constant regardless of calcium intake. Increasing dietary calcium results in minor increases in blood calcium. However, this is not a significant mechanism supporting osteoblast bone formation, except in the condition of low dietary calcium; further, abnormally high dietary calcium raises the risk of serious health consequences not directly related to bone mass including [[Myocardial infarction|heart attack]] and [[stroke]].<ref name=\"pmid25491763\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Reid IR, Bristow SM, Bolland MJ | title = Cardiovascular complications of calcium supplements | journal = J. Cell. Biochem. | volume = 116 | issue = 4 | pages = 494\u2013501 | date = April 2015 | pmid = 25491763 | doi = 10.1002/jcb.25028 }}</ref> Intermittent PTH stimulation increases osteoblast activity, although PTH is bifunctional and mediates bone matrix degradation at higher concentrations.\n\nThe skeleton is also modified for reproduction and in response to nutritional and other [[hormone]] stresses; it responds to [[steroid]]s, including [[estrogen]] and [[glucocorticoid]]s, which are important in reproduction and energy metabolism regulation. Bone turnover involves major expenditures of energy for synthesis and degradation, involving many additional signals including [[pituitary]] hormones. Two of these are [[adrenocorticotropic hormone]] (ACTH)<ref name=\"pmid20421485\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Zaidi M, Sun L, Robinson LJ, Tourkova IL, Liu L, Wang Y, Zhu LL, Liu X, Li J, Peng Y, Yang G, Shi X, Levine A, Iqbal J, Yaroslavskiy BB, Isales C, Blair HC | title = ACTH protects against glucocorticoid-induced osteonecrosis of bone | journal = Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U.S.A. | volume = 107 | issue = 19 | pages = 8782\u20137 | date = May 2010 | pmid = 20421485 | pmc = 2889316 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.0912176107 | bibcode = 2010PNAS..107.8782Z }}</ref> and [[follicle stimulating hormone]].<ref name=\"pmid16630814\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Sun L, Peng Y, Sharrow AC, Iqbal J, Zhang Z, Papachristou DJ, Zaidi S, Zhu LL, Yaroslavskiy BB, Zhou H, Zallone A, Sairam MR, Kumar TR, Bo W, Braun J, Cardoso-Landa L, Schaffler MB, Moonga BS, Blair HC, Zaidi M | title = FSH directly regulates bone mass | journal = Cell | volume = 125 | issue = 2 | pages = 247\u201360 | date = April 2006 | pmid = 16630814 | doi = 10.1016/j.cell.2006.01.051 }}</ref> The physiological role for responses to these, and several other [[glycoprotein]] hormones, is not fully understood, although it is likely that ACTH is bifunctional, like PTH, supporting bone formation with periodic spikes of ACTH, but causing bone destruction in large concentrations. In mice, mutations that reduce the efficiency of ACTH-induced glucocorticoid production in the adrenals cause the skeleton to become dense ([[Osteosclerosis|osteosclerotic]] bone).<ref name=\"pmid18204096\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Hoekstra M, Meurs I, Koenders M, Out R, Hildebrand RB, Kruijt JK, Van Eck M, Van Berkel TJ | title = Absence of HDL cholesteryl ester uptake in mice via SR-BI impairs an adequate adrenal glucocorticoid-mediated stress response to fasting | journal = J. Lipid Res. | volume = 49 | issue = 4 | pages = 738\u201345 | date = April 2008 | pmid = 18204096 | doi = 10.1194/jlr.M700475-JLR200 }}</ref><ref name=\"pmid24253048\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Martineau C, Martin-Falstrault L, Brissette L, Moreau R | title = The atherogenic Scarb1 null mouse model shows a high bone mass phenotype | journal = Am. J. Physiol. Endocrinol. Metab. | volume = 306 | issue = 1 | pages = E48\u201357 | date = January 2014 | pmid = 24253048 | pmc = 3920004 | doi = 10.1152/ajpendo.00421.2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Organization and ultrastructure==\nIn well-preserved bone studied at high magnification via [[electron microscope|electron microscopy]], individual osteoblasts are shown to be connected by [[tight junctions]], which prevent [[extracellular fluid]] passage and thus create a bone compartment separate from the general extracellular fluid.<ref name=\"pmid8527235\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Arana-Chavez VE, Soares AM, Katchburian E | title = Junctions between early developing osteoblasts of rat calvaria as revealed by freeze-fracture and ultrathin section electron microscopy | journal = Arch. Histol. Cytol. | volume = 58 | issue = 3 | pages = 285\u201392 | date = August 1995 | pmid = 8527235 | doi=10.1679/aohc.58.285}}</ref> The osteoblasts are also connected by [[gap junction]]s, small pores that connect osteoblasts, allowing the cells in one cohort to function as a unit.<ref name=\"pmid6797704\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Doty SB | title = Morphological evidence of gap junctions between bone cells | journal = Calcif. Tissue Int. | volume = 33 | issue = 5 | pages = 509\u201312 | date = 1981 | pmid = 6797704 | doi = 10.1007/BF02409482 }}</ref> The gap junctions also connect deeper layers of cells to the surface layer (''osteocytes'' when surrounded by bone). This was demonstrated directly by injecting low [[molecular weight]] [[Fluorophore|fluorescent dyes]] into osteoblasts and showing that the dye diffused to surrounding and deeper cells in the bone-forming unit.<ref name=\"pmid10703922\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Yellowley CE, Li Z, Zhou Z, Jacobs CR, Donahue HJ | title = Functional gap junctions between osteocytic and osteoblastic cells | journal = J. Bone Miner. Res. | volume = 15 | issue = 2 | pages = 209\u201317 | date = February 2000 | pmid = 10703922 | doi = 10.1359/jbmr.2000.15.2.209 }}</ref> Bone is composed of many of these units, which are separated by impermeable zones with no cellular connections, called cement lines.\n\n==Collagen and accessory proteins==\nAlmost all of the organic (non-mineral) component of bone is dense [[collagen]] type I,<ref name=\"pmid271986\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Reddi AH, Gay R, Gay S, Miller EJ | title = Transitions in collagen types during matrix-induced cartilage, bone, and bone marrow formation | journal = Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U.S.A. | volume = 74 | issue = 12 | pages = 5589\u201392 | date = December 1977 | pmid = 271986 | pmc = 431820 | doi=10.1073/pnas.74.12.5589| bibcode = 1977PNAS...74.5589R }}</ref> which forms dense crosslinked ropes that give bone its tensile strength. By mechanisms still unclear, osteoblasts secrete layers of oriented collagen, with the layers parallel to the long axis of the bone alternating with layers at right angles to the long axis of the bone every few [[micrometers]]. Defects in collagen type I cause the commonest inherited disorder of bone, called [[osteogenesis imperfecta]].<ref name=\"pmid2010058\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Kuivaniemi H, Tromp G, Prockop DJ | title = Mutations in collagen genes: causes of rare and some common diseases in humans | journal = FASEB J. | volume = 5 | issue = 7 | pages = 2052\u201360 | date = April 1991 | pmid = 2010058 | doi = 10.1096/fasebj.5.7.2010058 }}</ref>\n\nMinor, but important, amounts of small proteins, including [[osteocalcin]] and [[osteopontin]], are secreted in bone's organic matrix.<ref name=\"pmid8579903\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Aubin JE, Liu F, Malaval L, Gupta AK | title = Osteoblast and chondroblast differentiation | journal = Bone | volume = 17 | issue = 2 Suppl | pages = 77S\u201383S | date = August 1995 | pmid = 8579903 | doi = 10.1016/8756-3282(95)00183-E }}</ref> Osteocalcin is not expressed at significant concentrations except in bone, and thus osteocalcin is a specific marker for bone matrix synthesis.<ref name=\"pmid2939433\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Delmas PD, Demiaux B, Malaval L, Chapuy MC, Meunier PJ | title = [Osteocalcin (or bone gla-protein), a new biological marker for studying bone pathology] | language = French | journal = Presse Med | volume = 15 | issue = 14 | pages = 643\u20136 | date = April 1986 | pmid = 2939433 }}</ref> These proteins link organic and mineral component of bone matrix.<ref name=\"pmid8075622\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Roach HI | title = Why does bone matrix contain non-collagenous proteins? The possible roles of osteocalcin, osteonectin, osteopontin and bone sialoprotein in bone mineralisation and resorption | journal = Cell Biol. Int. | volume = 18 | issue = 6 | pages = 617\u201328 | date = June 1994 | pmid = 8075622 | doi = 10.1006/cbir.1994.1088 }}</ref> The proteins are necessary for maximal matrix strength due to their intermediate localization between mineral and collagen.\n\nHowever, in mice where expression of osteocalcin or osteopontin was eliminated by targeted disruption of the respective genes ([[knockout mice]]), accumulation of mineral was not notably affected, indicating that organization of matrix is not significantly related to mineral transport.<ref name=\"pmid9737340\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Boskey AL, Gadaleta S, Gundberg C, Doty SB, Ducy P, Karsenty G | title = Fourier transform infrared microspectroscopic analysis of bones of osteocalcin-deficient mice provides insight into the function of osteocalcin | journal = Bone | volume = 23 | issue = 3 | pages = 187\u201396 | date = September 1998 | pmid = 9737340 | doi=10.1016/s8756-3282(98)00092-1}}</ref><ref name=\"pmid20171304\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Thurner PJ, Chen CG, Ionova-Martin S, Sun L, Harman A, Porter A, Ager JW, Ritchie RO, Alliston T | title = Osteopontin deficiency increases bone fragility but preserves bone mass | journal = Bone | volume = 46 | issue = 6 | pages = 1564\u201373 | date = June 2010 | pmid = 20171304 | pmc = 2875278 | doi = 10.1016/j.bone.2010.02.014 }}</ref>\n\n==Bone versus cartilage==\nThe primitive skeleton is [[cartilage]], a solid avascular (without blood vessels) tissue in which individual cartilage-matrix secreting cells, or [[chondrocyte]]s, occur. Chondrocytes do not have intercellular connections and are not coordinated in units. Cartilage is composed of a network of [[collagen]] type II held in tension by water-absorbing proteins, hydrophilic [[proteoglycan]]s.<ref name=\"pmid12023876\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Blair HC, Zaidi M, Schlesinger PH | title = Mechanisms balancing skeletal matrix synthesis and degradation | journal = Biochem. J. | volume = 364 | issue = Pt 2 | pages = 329\u201341 | date = June 2002 | pmid = 12023876 | doi = 10.1042/BJ20020165 | pmc = 1222578 }}</ref> This is the adult skeleton in [[Chondrichthyes|cartilaginous fishes]] such as [[shark]]s. It develops as the initial skeleton in more advanced [[Class (biology)|classes]] of animals.\n\nIn air-breathing vertebrates, cartilage is replaced by cellular bone. A transitional tissue is mineralized [[cartilage]]. Cartilage mineralizes by massive expression of phosphate-producing enzymes, which cause high local concentrations of calcium and phosphate that precipitate.<ref name=\"pmid12023876\"/> This mineralized cartilage is not dense or strong. In the air breathing vertebrates it is used as a scaffold for formation of cellular bone made by osteoblasts, and then it is removed by [[osteoclasts]], which specialize in degrading mineralized tissue.\n\nOsteoblasts produce an advanced type of bone matrix consisting of dense, irregular crystals of [[hydroxyapatite]], packed around the collagen ropes.<ref name=\"pmid21674636\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Blair HC, Robinson LJ, Huang CL, Sun L, Friedman PA, Schlesinger PH, Zaidi M | title = Calcium and bone disease | journal = BioFactors | volume = 37 | issue = 3 | pages = 159\u201367 | date = 2011 | pmid = 21674636 | pmc = 3608212 | doi = 10.1002/biof.143 }}</ref> This is a strong composite material that allows the skeleton to be shaped mainly as hollow tubes. Reducing the long bones to tubes reduces weight while maintaining strength.\n\n==Mineralization of bone==\nThe mechanisms of mineralization are not fully understood. Fluorescent, low-molecular weight compounds such as [[tetracycline]] or [[calcein]] bind strongly to bone mineral, when administered for short periods. They then accumulate in narrow bands in the new bone.<ref name=\"pmid4894738\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Frost HM | title = Tetracycline-based histological analysis of bone remodeling | journal = Calcif Tissue Res | volume = 3 | issue = 3 | pages = 211\u201337 | date = 1969 | pmid = 4894738 | doi = 10.1007/BF02058664 }}</ref> These bands run across the contiguous group of bone-forming osteoblasts. They occur at a narrow (sub-[[micrometer]]) mineralization front. Most bone surfaces express no new bone formation, no tetracycline uptake and no mineral formation. This strongly suggests that facilitated or [[active transport]], coordinated across the bone-forming group, is involved in bone formation, and that only cell-mediated mineral formation occurs. That is, dietary calcium does not create mineral by mass action.\n\nThe mechanism of mineral formation in bone is clearly distinct from the [[phylogenetic]]ally older process by which cartilage is mineralized: tetracycline does not label mineralized cartilage at narrow bands or in specific sites, but diffusely, in keeping with a passive mineralization mechanism.<ref name=\"pmid21674636\"/>\n\nOsteoblasts separate bone from the extracellular fluid by tight junctions <ref name=\"pmid8527235\"/> by regulated transport. Unlike in cartilage, [[phosphate]] and [[calcium]] cannot move in or out by passive diffusion, because the [[tight junction|tight osteoblast junction]]s isolate the bone formation space. Calcium is transported across osteoblasts by [[facilitated transport]] (that is, by passive transporters, which do not pump calcium against a gradient).<ref name=\"pmid21674636\"/> In contrast, phosphate is actively produced by a combination of secretion of phosphate-containing compounds, including [[Adenosine triphosphate|ATP]], and by [[phosphatase]]s that cleave phosphate to create a high phosphate concentration at the mineralization front. [[Alkaline phosphatase]] is a membrane-anchored protein that is a characteristic marker expressed in large amounts at the apical (secretory) face of active osteoblasts.\n\n[[File:Osteoblast Organization.jpg|thumb|'''Major features of the bone-forming complex''', the osteon, composed of osteoblasts and osteocytes.]]\n\nAt least one more regulated transport process is involved. The [[stoichiometry]] of bone mineral basically is that of [[Hydroxylapatite|hydroxyapatite]] precipitating from phosphate, calcium, and water at a slightly alkaline [[pH]]:<ref name=\"Neuman1958\">{{cite book|vauthors = Neuman WF, Neuman MW|title=The Chemical Dynamics of Bone Mineral|url = https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.550358|date=1958-01-01|publisher = University of Chicago Press|isbn = 0-226-57512-8}}{{pn|date=October 2019}}</ref>\n\n               '''6 HPO<sub>4</sub><sup>2\u2212</sup> + 2 H<sub>2</sub>O + 10 Ca<sup>2+</sup> \u21cc Ca<sub>10</sub>(PO<sub>4</sub>)<sub>6</sub>(OH)<sub>2</sub> + {{color|red|8 H<sup>+</sup>}}'''\n\nIn a closed system as mineral precipitates, acid accumulates, rapidly lowering the [[pH]] and stopping further precipitation. Cartilage presents no barrier to diffusion and acid therefore diffuses away, allowing precipitation to continue. In the osteon, where matrix is separated from extracellular fluid by tight junctions, this cannot occur. In the controlled, sealed compartment, removing H<sup>+</sup> drives precipitation under a wide variety of extracellular conditions, as long as calcium and phosphate are available in the matrix compartment.<ref name=\"pmid14498063\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Schartum S, Nichols G | title = Concerning pH gradients between the extracellular compartment and fluids bathing the bone mineral surface and their relation to calcium ion distribution | journal = J. Clin. Invest. | volume = 41 | issue = 5| pages = 1163\u20138 | date = May 1962 | pmid = 14498063 | pmc = 291024 | doi = 10.1172/JCI104569 }}</ref> The mechanism by which acid transits the barrier layer remains uncertain. Osteoblasts have capacity for Na<sup>+</sup>/H<sup>+</sup> exchange via the redundant Na/H exchangers, NHE1 and NHE6.<ref name=\"pmid21413028\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Liu L, Schlesinger PH, Slack NM, Friedman PA, Blair HC | title = High capacity Na+/H+ exchange activity in mineralizing osteoblasts | journal = J. Cell. Physiol. | volume = 226 | issue = 6 | pages = 1702\u201312 | date = June 2011 | pmid = 21413028 | pmc = 4458346 | doi = 10.1002/jcp.22501 }}</ref> This H<sup>+</sup> exchange is a major element in acid removal, although the mechanism by which H<sup>+</sup> is transported from the matrix space into the barrier osteoblast is not known.\n\nIn bone removal, a reverse transport mechanism uses acid delivered to the mineralized matrix to drive hydroxyapatite into solution.<ref name=\"pmid2528207\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Blair HC, Teitelbaum SL, Ghiselli R, Gluck S | title = Osteoclastic bone resorption by a polarized vacuolar proton pump | journal = Science | volume = 245 | issue = 4920 | pages = 855\u20137 | date = August 1989 | pmid = 2528207 | doi=10.1126/science.2528207| bibcode = 1989Sci...245..855B }}</ref>\n\n== Osteocyte feedback ==\nFeedback from physical activity maintains bone mass, while feedback from osteocytes limits the size of the bone-forming unit.<ref name=\"pmid16036059\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Klein-Nulend J, Nijweide PJ, Burger EH | title = Osteocyte and bone structure | journal = Curr Osteoporos Rep | volume = 1 | issue = 1 | pages = 5\u201310 | date = June 2003 | pmid = 16036059 | doi=10.1007/s11914-003-0002-y}}</ref> An important additional mechanism is secretion by osteocytes, buried in the matrix, of [[sclerostin]], a protein that inhibits a pathway that maintains osteoblast activity. Thus, when the osteon reaches a limiting size, it deactivates bone synthesis.<ref name=\"pmid17118265\">{{cite book |doi=10.1016/S0070-2153(06)76004-5 |pmid=17118265 |chapter=WNT Signaling: A Key Regulator of Bone Mass |volume=76 |pages=103\u2013127 |title=Current Topics in Developmental Biology |year=2006 |last1=Baron |first1=Roland |last2=Rawadi |first2=Georges |last3=Roman\u2010Roman |first3=Sergio |isbn=978-0-12-153176-8 }}</ref>\n\n==Morphology and histological staining==\n\n[[H&E stain|Hematoxylin and eosin]] staining (H&E) shows that the cytoplasm of active osteoblasts is slightly [[basophilic]] due to the substantial presence of [[Endoplasmic reticulum#Rough endoplasmic reticulum|rough endoplasmic reticulum]]. The active osteoblast produces substantial collagen type I. About 10% of the bone matrix is collagen with the balance mineral.<ref name=\"Neuman1958\"/> The osteoblast's nucleus is spherical and large. An active osteoblast is characterized morphologically by a prominent [[Golgi apparatus]] that appears histologically as a clear zone adjacent to the nucleus. The products of the cell are mostly for transport into the osteoid, the non-mineralized matrix. Active osteoblasts can be labeled by antibodies to [[Type-I collagen]], or using naphthol phosphate and the [[Diazonium compound|diazonium]] dye fast blue to demonstrate alkaline phosphatase [[enzyme]] activity directly.\n\n<gallery>\nImage:Osteoblast.jpg | Osteoblast (Wright Giemsa stain, 100x) \nImage:Active osteoblasts.jpg |[[Micrograph|Light micrograph]] of [[Bone decalcification|decalcified]]  cancellous bone displaying osteoblasts actively synthesizing osteoid, containing two osteocytes.\nImage:Bony_nidus_2.jpg|[[Micrograph|Light micrograph]] of undecalcified tissue displaying osteoblasts actively synthesizing osteoid (center).\nImage:Bony_nidus_3.jpg|[[Micrograph|Light micrograph]] of undecalcified tissue displaying osteoblasts actively synthesizing rudimentary bone tissue (center).\nImage:Bone_hypercalcemia_-_2_-_very_high_mag.jpg|Osteoblasts lining bone (H&E stain).\n</gallery>\n\n\n\n==Isolation of Osteoblasts==\n#The first isolation technique by microdissection method was originally described by Fell et al.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Fell |first1=HB |title=The Osteogenic Capacity in vitro of Periosteum and Endosteum Isolated from the Limb Skeleton of Fowl Embryos and Young Chicks. |journal=Journal of Anatomy |date=January 1932 |volume=66 |issue=Pt 2 |pages=157\u2013180.11 |pmid=17104365 |pmc=1248877 }}</ref> using chick limb bones which were separated into periosteum and remaining parts. She obtained cells which possessed osteogenic characteristics from cultured tissue</ref> using chick limb bones which were separated into periosteum and remaining parts. She obtained cells which possessed osteogenic characteristics from cultured tissue. \n#Enzymatic digestion is one of the most advanced techniques for isolating bone cell populations and obtaining osteoblasts. Peck et al. (1964)<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Peck |first1=W. A. |last2=Birge |first2=S. J. |last3=Fedak |first3=S. A. |title=Bone Cells: Biochemical and Biological Studies after Enzymatic Isolation |journal=Science |date=11 December 1964 |volume=146 |issue=3650 |pages=1476\u20131477 |doi=10.1126/science.146.3650.1476 |pmid=14208576 |bibcode=1964Sci...146.1476P }}</ref> described the original method that is now often used by many researchers.\n#In 1974 Jones et al.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Jones |first1=S.J. |last2=Boyde |first2=A. |title=Some morphological observations on osteoclasts |journal=Cell and Tissue Research |date=December 1977 |volume=185 |issue=3 |pages=387\u201397 |doi=10.1007/bf00220298 |pmid=597853 }}</ref> found that osteoblasts moved laterally in vivo and in vitro under different experimental conditions and escribed the migration method in detail. The osteoblasts were, however, contaminated by cells migrating from the vascular openings, which might include endothelial cells and fibroblasts.\n\n== See also ==\n*[[List of human cell types derived from the germ layers]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*[[William F. Neuman]] and Margaret W. Neuman. (1958). The Chemical Dynamics of Bone Mineral. Chicago: The University of Chicago Press. {{ISBN|0-226-57512-8}}.\n*[[Frank H. Netter|Netter, Frank H.]] (1987). ''Musculoskeletal system: anatomy, physiology, and metabolic disorders''. Summit, New Jersey: Ciba-Geigy Corporation {{ISBN|0-914168-88-6}}.\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Bone and cartilage}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Skeletal system]]\n[[Category:Connective tissue cells]]\n[[Category:Human cells]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "Journal cites:, added 1 issue number", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Osteoblast"}
